export default "<!-- target: ja | interface: en | version: 1 -->\n<!-- Japanese. Extra chapters: three writing systems (hiragana/katakana/kanji), core particles (は vs が dedicated section), counters + あります/います, こそあど demonstratives, three verb groups (ichidan/godan/irregular), て-form and its uses, i-adj vs na-adj conjugation, sentence-final ね/よ, politeness levels + keigo intro, four conditionals (と/ば/たら/なら). -->\n\n# The Three Writing Systems <!-- slug: writing-systems -->\n\nJapanese uses **three scripts simultaneously** — sometimes in a single sentence. This is the first thing to understand, because it explains why Japanese looks chaotic at first and highly structured once you see the logic.\n\n## Hiragana (ひらがな) <!-- slug: hiragana -->\n\n46 syllable symbols. **All native Japanese grammar is written in hiragana** — verb endings, particles, conjunctions, grammatical words. You must learn hiragana first; it's the skeleton of the language. Learnable in a week with daily practice.\n\nEach symbol represents a consonant+vowel mora (or a bare vowel): *か (ka), き (ki), く (ku), け (ke), こ (ko)*. The vowels are pure: **a** (as in *father*), **i** (as in *bee*), **u** (as in *blue* — unrounded), **e** (as in *bet*), **o** (as in *more*).\n\n## Katakana (カタカナ) <!-- slug: katakana -->\n\n46 symbols, same sounds as hiragana, different shapes. **Katakana is used for foreign loanwords (gairaigo), foreign names, and emphasis**. If you see angular, sharp-cornered characters, it's katakana.\n\n*テレビ (terebi — TV), コーヒー (kōhī — coffee), アメリカ (Amerika — America), スマホ (sumaho — smartphone)*\n\nThe long vowel mark ー (chōonpu) extends the preceding vowel: *コーヒー* has two long vowels.\n\n## Kanji (漢字) <!-- slug: kanji -->\n\nChinese-derived logographic characters. Each has at least two readings: **on-yomi** (Chinese-derived, used in compound words) and **kun-yomi** (Japanese native reading, used standalone or with kana endings).\n\n*山 (yama / san — mountain), 水 (mizu / sui — water), 人 (hito / jin/nin — person)*\n\nThere are ~2,000 characters in the standard joyo kanji set (taught through high school). You don't need all of them to have real conversations, but reading anything authentic requires building a kanji base gradually.\n\n## How they combine\n\nA single sentence uses all three:\n*私はコーヒーを飲みます。* (Watashi wa kōhī o nomimasu.) — I drink coffee.\n\n- 私 = kanji (watashi — I)\n- は = hiragana (wa — topic particle)\n- コーヒー = katakana (kōhī — coffee, loanword)\n- を = hiragana (o — object particle)\n- 飲みます = kanji + hiragana (nomi-masu — drink [polite])\n\nPractical advice: learn hiragana and katakana before anything else. Apps like Anki with mnemonics get most learners through both in 2–3 weeks. Kanji is a long game — start with the most frequent 100 and grow from there.\n\n---\n\n# Pronunciation <!-- slug: pronunciation -->\n\n## Mora timing\n\nJapanese is **mora-timed**, not syllable-timed. Each mora takes approximately equal time. This means *さっき (sakki — a moment ago)* has 3 morae (sa-k-ki) not 2 syllables — the double consonant (っ/ッ) is a full mora of silence before the consonant.\n\nLong vowels also count as 2 morae: *おかあさん (okāsan — mother)* = o-ka-a-sa-n = 5 morae. Shortening long vowels changes or destroys meaning.\n\n## Particles as pronounced\n\nThree hiragana have unexpected readings as particles:\n- **は** (ha) → read as **wa** when used as topic particle\n- **を** (wo) → read as **o** when used as object particle\n- **へ** (he) → read as **e** when used as direction particle\n\n## Pitch accent\n\nJapanese has **pitch accent** — words are distinguished by a pattern of high (H) and low (L) tones, not by stress as in English. The exact pattern varies by region (Tokyo dialect is standard).\n\n*橋 hashi* (bridge) H-L vs *箸 hashi* (chopsticks) L-H — same romanization, different meaning, different pitch.\n\nFor beginners: pitch accent won't prevent communication, but listening carefully to native speakers and mimicking their intonation is more important than in English.\n\n## Consonant notes\n\n- **r** (ら り る れ ろ) — a light tap, between English r and l. Not a rolled r, not an English r. Your tongue taps once behind the upper teeth, like a very light d.\n- **fu** (ふ) — a bilabial fricative, not quite English \"f\" (which uses teeth). Lips barely touch, breath passes through.\n- Double consonants (っ) — a held beat of silence: *きって (kitte — stamp)* vs *きて (kite — come [te-form])* — these are different words.\n\n---\n\n# Basic Sentence Structure & Core Particles <!-- slug: particles -->\n\nParticles are the most important thing in Japanese grammar. They are **postpositions** — they follow the word they mark, opposite to English prepositions. Particles do what word order and prepositions do in English.\n\nJapanese default word order is **SOV: Subject – Object – Verb**. The verb goes at the end. Always.\n\n*私は本を読みます。* (Watashi **wa** hon **o** yomimasu.) — I read books. (lit: I-TOPIC book-OBJECT read-POLITE)\n\nYou can rearrange most elements and it remains grammatical (the particles carry the meaning), but the verb stays last.\n\n## は vs が — the famous distinction <!-- slug: wa-vs-ga -->\n\nThis is the distinction that trips up every Japanese learner for months. Both relate to the subject — but they do completely different things.\n\n**は (wa) — Topic Marker**\n\nは marks what the sentence is **about**. It establishes the topic of conversation. It can mark subjects, objects, time expressions — any element elevated to \"topic.\" It often implies contrast.\n\n**が (ga) — Subject Marker**\n\nが marks the **grammatical subject** — the agent of the verb. It highlights the *identity* of who does something, often in answer to \"who?\" It does not imply contrast.\n\nThe difference in practice:\n\n| Japanese | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| 私**は**学生です。 (Watashi wa gakusei desu.) | **As for me**, I am a student. (introducing myself, topic) |\n| 私**が**学生です。 (Watashi ga gakusei desu.) | **I** am the student. (not someone else — identifying) |\n| 猫**は**魚を食べます。 (Neko wa sakana o tabemasu.) | **As for cats**, they eat fish. (general statement about cats) |\n| 猫**が**魚を食べました。 (Neko ga sakana o tabemashita.) | **The cat** ate the fish. (identifying: it was the cat, not the dog) |\n\nMore rules:\n- New information is marked with が: *あ、猫がいる！ (A, neko ga iru!) — Oh, there's a cat!*\n- Known/previously mentioned topic switches to は: *猫はかわいいです。 (The cat is cute.)*\n- Certain verbs always take が for their subject: *わかる (wakaru — understand), できる (dekiru — can do), ある/いる (there is), 好き (suki — like), 欲しい (hoshii — want)*: *コーヒーが好きです。 (I like coffee.)* ✗ ~~コーヒーをすきです~~\n- は in negative/contrast sentences: *魚**は**食べません。* (Fish, I don't eat — implying I eat other things.)\n\nMnemonic: **は = As for…** / **が = IT IS … (who/what)**. Read every は sentence as \"As for [topic]…\"\n\n## を (o) — Object Marker\n\nMarks the **direct object** of transitive verbs. Straightforward:\n*本を読む (hon o yomu — read a book) | 水を飲む (mizu o nomu — drink water) | 音楽を聞く (ongaku o kiku — listen to music)*\n\nAlso marks the space traversed with motion verbs: *公園を歩く (kōen o aruku — walk through the park)*\n\n## に (ni) — Time / Destination / Indirect Object <!-- slug: ni-particle -->\n\nに is the workhorse particle with three major uses:\n\n**1. Specific point in time:**\n*三時に (san-ji ni — at 3 o'clock) | 月曜日に (getsuyōbi ni — on Monday) | 2024年に (2024-nen ni — in 2024)*\n⚠️ No に with relative time words: *今日 (kyō — today), 明日 (ashita — tomorrow), 毎日 (mainichi — every day)* — no particle.\n\n**2. Destination of movement:**\n*東京に行く (Tōkyō ni iku — go to Tokyo) | 家に帰る (ie ni kaeru — return home) | 学校に来る (gakkō ni kuru — come to school)*\n\n**3. Indirect object (recipient):**\n*友達に電話する (tomodachi ni denwa suru — call a friend) | 先生に聞く (sensei ni kiku — ask the teacher) | 彼女に手紙を書く (kanojo ni tegami o kaku — write a letter to her)*\n\n**4. Location of existence (with ある/いる):**\n*駅に自販機がある。 (Eki ni jidōhanbaiki ga aru.) — There is a vending machine at the station.*\n\n## へ (e) — Direction\n\nMarks direction of movement. Similar to に for movement, but emphasizes the **direction** rather than the destination:\n*東へ行く (higashi e iku — go toward the east)*\nIn daily speech, に and へ are often interchangeable for movement.\n\n## で (de) — Location of Action / Means <!-- slug: de-particle -->\n\n**Location where an action takes place** (contrast with に which marks existence/destination):\n*図書館で勉強する (toshokan de benkyō suru — study at the library)*\n*レストランで食べる (resutoran de taberu — eat at a restaurant)*\n\n**Means or method:**\n*電車で行く (densha de iku — go by train) | 日本語で話す (nihongo de hanasu — speak in Japanese) | 箸で食べる (hashi de taberu — eat with chopsticks)*\n\n**で vs に location distinction:**\n- *図書館**に**います。 (Toshokan ni imasu.) — I am at the library.* (existence — に)\n- *図書館**で**勉強します。 (Toshokan de benkyō shimasu.) — I study at the library.* (action — で)\n\n## と (to) — With / And (exhaustive list)\n\n*友達と行く (tomodachi to iku — go with a friend)*\n*りんごとみかんを買った (ringo to mikan o katta — bought apples AND oranges)* — と lists exhaustively (these things, no others). For non-exhaustive \"and\" between nouns: use や.\n\n## から / まで (kara / made) — From / Until\n\n*東京から大阪まで (Tōkyō kara Ōsaka made — from Tokyo to Osaka)*\n*9時から5時まで働く (ku-ji kara go-ji made hataraku — work from 9 to 5)*\n\n## の (no) — Possessive / Linking\n\n*私の本 (watashi no hon — my book) | 日本語の先生 (nihongo no sensei — Japanese teacher)*\nの can chain: *私の大学の友達 (my university friend)*\nAlso makes a noun out of a clause: *好きなの (sukina no — the one I like)*\n\n## も (mo) — Also / Even\n\nReplaces は or が (never stacks): *私も行きます。 (Watashi mo ikimasu.) — I'm going too.*\nWith negatives: *私も行きません。 — I'm not going either.*\n\n## か (ka) — Question Marker\n\nTurns a sentence into a yes/no question (polite speech — see Questions chapter).\n\n---\n\n# Nouns, Counters & There-Is <!-- slug: nouns-counters -->\n\n## No plural, no gender, no articles\n\nJapanese nouns do not change form. *猫 (neko)* can mean \"a cat,\" \"the cat,\" \"cats,\" or \"the cats\" — context determines which. There is no grammatical gender.\n\n*犬が好きです。 (Inu ga suki desu.)* — I like dogs / I like a dog / I like the dog.\n\n## Counters (助数詞 josūshi)\n\nJapanese cannot attach bare numbers to nouns — a **counter word** is always needed. Each category of thing has its own counter:\n\n| Counter | Reading | Used for | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 人 | -ri (1,2), -nin (3+) | people | 一人 (hitori), 二人 (futari), 三人 (san-nin) |\n| 個 | -ko | small objects | りんご三個 (ringo san-ko — 3 apples) |\n| 枚 | -mai | flat things | 紙一枚 (kami ichi-mai — 1 sheet of paper) |\n| 本 | -hon/-pon/-bon | long thin things | ペン二本 (pen ni-hon — 2 pens) |\n| 冊 | -satsu | bound books | 本三冊 (hon san-satsu — 3 books) |\n| 台 | -dai | machines/vehicles | 車一台 (kuruma ichi-dai — 1 car) |\n| 匹 | -hiki/-piki | small animals | 猫二匹 (neko ni-hiki — 2 cats) |\n| 頭 | -tō | large animals | 牛三頭 (ushi san-tō — 3 cows) |\n| 杯 | -hai/-pai/-bai | cups/bowls | コーヒー一杯 (kōhī ippai — 1 cup of coffee) |\n| つ | -tsu | general (1-9 only) | 一つ、二つ、三つ… (hitotsu, futatsu, mittsu…) |\n\nThe つ counter is native Japanese (not Sino-Japanese) and works as a default for miscellaneous objects up to 9. After 10, use specific counters or 個.\n\nNote: reading changes happen (hon → pon/bon, hiki → piki/biki) depending on the preceding number — these are rendaku (sequential voicing) and must be memorized per counter. Learning the top 6–8 counters covers most daily needs.\n\n## There-is: あります vs います <!-- slug: arimasu-imasu -->\n\nTwo verbs for \"there is / to exist\" — choosing wrong marks you as a beginner:\n\n- **あります (arimasu)** — for inanimate things (objects, plants)\n- **います (imasu)** — for animate beings (people, animals)\n\n*机の上に本があります。 (Tsukue no ue ni hon ga arimasu.)* — There is a book on the desk.\n*公園に子供がいます。 (Kōen ni kodomo ga imasu.)* — There are children in the park.\n*ここに猫がいます。 (Koko ni neko ga imasu.)* — There is a cat here. (cat = animate → います)\n\nNegative: *ありません (arimasen) / いません (imasen)*\nPlain form: *ある / いる*\n\n---\n\n# Pronouns & こそあど Demonstratives <!-- slug: pronouns-demonstratives -->\n\n## Personal pronouns\n\nJapanese has many \"I\" and \"you\" words, all carrying social nuance:\n\n| Meaning | Word | Register |\n|---|---|---|\n| I | 私 (watashi) | neutral, polite |\n| I | 僕 (boku) | masculine, informal |\n| I | 俺 (ore) | masculine, rough |\n| I | あたし (atashi) | feminine, casual |\n| you | あなた (anata) | polite but often avoided |\n| you | 君 (kimi) | informal, male speech |\n| you | お前 (omae) | rough, can be rude |\n\nIn practice, **Japanese speakers often omit pronouns entirely** — subject and object are inferred from context. Saying あなた to someone you know their name sounds oddly distant; use their name or title instead.\n\nThird person: 彼 (kare — he), 彼女 (kanojo — she). These also mean \"boyfriend/girlfriend\" — context matters.\n\n## こそあど (ko-so-a-do) — the demonstrative system <!-- slug: kosoado -->\n\nJapanese organizes demonstratives into a beautifully regular 4-way system based on distance:\n\n| | Near speaker (ko-) | Near listener (so-) | Far from both (a-) | Unknown/question (do-) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| thing | これ (kore — this) | それ (sore — that) | あれ (are — that over there) | どれ (dore — which) |\n| place | ここ (koko — here) | そこ (soko — there) | あそこ (asoko — over there) | どこ (doko — where) |\n| direction | こちら (kochira) | そちら (sochira) | あちら (achira) | どちら (dochira) |\n| adj/noun modifier | この (kono — this N) | その (sono — that N) | あの (ano — that N over there) | どの (dono — which N) |\n| manner | こう (kō — this way) | そう (sō — that way) | ああ (ā — that way) | どう (dō — how) |\n\n*これは何ですか？ (Kore wa nan desu ka?) — What is this?*\n*あの映画が好きです。 (Ano eiga ga suki desu.) — I like that movie (over there / we both know which one).*\n\nあの in conversation often refers to something both speakers know: *あの映画* = \"that movie [we both know about].\"\nそう (sō) is behind the ubiquitous response *そうですか (Sō desu ka?) — Is that so? / I see.*\n\n---\n\n# Questions <!-- slug: questions -->\n\n## Yes/no questions\n\nIn **polite speech**, add **か (ka)** to the end of a statement:\n*これは本ですか？ (Kore wa hon desu ka?) — Is this a book?*\n*日本語を話しますか？ (Nihongo o hanashimasu ka?) — Do you speak Japanese?*\n\nIn **casual speech**, か alone can sound harsh (masculine/rough). Rising intonation alone works: *これ本？ (Kore, hon?) — This, a book?*\n\nAnswering:\n- *はい (hai) — yes* / *いいえ (iie) — no*\n- Softened yes: *そうです (sō desu) — that's right* | Softened no: *ちょっと… (chotto… — a little… [politely declining])*\n\nIn Japanese, yes/no answers confirm or deny the **fact**, not the grammar. *日本語を話しませんか？ (Don't you speak Japanese?) → はい、話しません (Yes, I don't speak it) / いいえ、話します (No, I do speak it).* — The reverse of English!\n\n## Question words\n\n| Japanese | Rōmaji | English |\n|---|---|---|\n| 何 | nani / nan | what |\n| 誰 | dare | who |\n| どこ | doko | where |\n| いつ | itsu | when |\n| なぜ / どうして | naze / dōshite | why |\n| どう | dō | how |\n| どんな | donna | what kind of |\n| いくつ | ikutsu | how many (things) |\n| いくら | ikura | how much (price) |\n| どのくらい | dono kurai | how long/far |\n\nQuestion words go where the answer would be — no inversion, no do-support:\n*彼は何を食べますか？ (Kare wa nani o tabemasu ka?) — What does he eat?*\n*あなたはどこに住んでいますか？ (Anata wa doko ni sunde imasu ka?) — Where do you live?*\n\n---\n\n# Verbs — Three Groups <!-- slug: verb-groups -->\n\nJapanese verbs inflect heavily, but the system is highly regular once you know which of three groups a verb belongs to.\n\n## Group 1 — Godan verbs (五段動詞) <!-- slug: godan -->\n\n\"5-step\" verbs. Dictionary form ends in any う-row syllable: *ku, gu, su, tsu, nu, bu, mu, ru, u*. The final syllable \"steps\" through 5 rows of the kana table to make different forms.\n\nCommon examples: *書く (kaku — write), 話す (hanasu — speak), 飲む (nomu — drink), 読む (yomu — read), 行く (iku — go), 聞く (kiku — listen), 買う (kau — buy), 待つ (matsu — wait), 乗る (noru — ride)*\n\n## Group 2 — Ichidan verbs (一段動詞) <!-- slug: ichidan -->\n\n\"1-step\" verbs. Dictionary form always ends in **-ru**, with **-i** or **-e** before the -ru. Only one change needed — just drop the -ru.\n\nCommon examples: *食べる (taberu — eat), 見る (miru — see), 起きる (okiru — wake up), 寝る (neru — sleep), 着る (kiru — wear), 教える (oshieru — teach), 開ける (akeru — open)*\n\n⚠️ Trap: some -ru verbs are actually Godan: *帰る (kaeru — return home), 走る (hashiru — run), 切る (kiru — cut), 入る (hairu — enter)*. These must be memorized.\n\nMnemonic: if there's an **i** or **e** sound directly before -ru, it's probably Ichidan. But always check for the exceptions.\n\n## Group 3 — Irregular (不規則動詞) <!-- slug: irregular-verbs -->\n\nOnly **two**: *する (suru — do)* and *来る (kuru — come)*. Memorize their conjugations — they appear constantly.\n\n## The polite ます-form\n\nAll three groups produce the polite ます form the same final way — attach ます to the verb stem. The stem is formed differently per group:\n\n| Group | Dictionary | Stem | ます form |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Godan (kaku) | 書く | 書き (kaki) | 書きます (kakimasu) |\n| Godan (nomu) | 飲む | 飲み (nomi) | 飲みます (nomimasu) |\n| Ichidan (taberu) | 食べる | 食べ (tabe) | 食べます (tabemasu) |\n| Irregular (suru) | する | し (shi) | します (shimasu) |\n| Irregular (kuru) | 来る | き (ki) | 来ます (kimasu) |\n\nFor Godan: the final う-row syllable shifts to its い-row counterpart: く→き, す→し, む→み, ぬ→に, ぶ→び, つ→ち, る→り, う→い, ぐ→ぎ.\n\nます conjugates: *ます (non-past positive) / ません (non-past negative) / ました (past positive) / ませんでした (past negative)*\n\n---\n\n# Verb Forms & \"Tense\" <!-- slug: verb-tense -->\n\nJapanese has **two tenses** (non-past and past) and two aspects (ongoing vs complete), not the elaborate tense system of European languages.\n\n## Non-past vs Past\n\n**Non-past** covers both present and future. Context (time words, particles) distinguishes:\n*毎日コーヒーを飲みます。 (Mainichi kōhī o nomimasu.)* — I drink coffee every day. (habit)\n*明日友達に会います。 (Ashita tomodachi ni aimasu.)* — I'll meet my friend tomorrow. (future)\n\n**Past (た-form)**: dictionary form → た-form. The suffix depends on the verb group:\n\n| Godan ending | Past suffix | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| く | いた | 書く → 書いた (kaita — wrote) |\n| ぐ | いだ | 泳ぐ → 泳いだ (oyoida — swam) |\n| す | した | 話す → 話した (hanashita — spoke) |\n| む/ぶ/ぬ | んだ | 飲む → 飲んだ (nonda — drank) |\n| つ/う/る (godan) | った | 待つ → 待った (matta — waited) |\n| る (ichidan) | た | 食べる → 食べた (tabeta — ate) |\n\nException: 行く (iku) → 行った (itta — NOT いいた). する → した. 来る → 来た (kita).\n\n## Negative ない-form\n\nNon-past negative: add **ない** to the negative stem.\n- Godan: final syllable shifts to あ-row + ない: *書く → 書か**ない**, 飲む → 飲ま**ない***, 行く → 行か**ない**\n- Ichidan: drop る + ない: *食べる → 食べ**ない***\n- Exception: verbs ending in う → わない: *買う → 買わない (kawanai)*\n- する → しない | 来る → 来ない (konai)\n\nPolite negative: ません (as above).\n\n## The て-form — the Swiss army knife <!-- slug: te-form -->\n\nThe て-form (te-form) is perhaps the most useful thing to learn in Japanese. It is formed like the past た-form but with て/で instead of た/だ.\n\nFormation: same rules as past, just swap た→て, だ→で:\n*書く → 書いて (kaite) | 飲む → 飲んで (nonde) | 食べる → 食べて (tabete) | する → して (shite) | 来る → 来て (kite)*\n\n**Uses of て-form:**\n\n**1. Requests (て + ください):**\n*書いてください。 (Kaite kudasai.)* — Please write. | *ちょっと待ってください。 (Chotto matte kudasai.)* — Please wait a moment.\nSofter: *〜てくれる？ (〜te kureru?)* — casual request between friends.\n\n**2. Linking actions in sequence:**\n*シャワーを浴びて、朝ごはんを食べました。 (Shawā o abite, asagohan o tabemashita.)* — I showered and (then) ate breakfast.\nThe て-form acts like \"and then\" — actions unfold in order.\n\n**3. 〜ている (te iru) — progressive / ongoing state:**\nThis construction covers two things English splits:\n- Action in progress now: *本を読んでいます。 (Hon o yonde imasu.)* — I am reading a book.\n- Resulting state (from a completed action): *結婚しています。 (Kekkon shite imasu.)* — I am married. (lit: I have married and am in that state) | *窓が開いています。 (Mado ga aite imasu.)* — The window is open. (lit: the window has opened and is in that state)\n\nThis second use is critical: many things English describes with adjectives, Japanese describes with 〜ている of a verb.\n\n**4. Asking/giving permission (〜ていい):**\n*ここに座ってもいいですか？ (Koko ni suwatte mo ii desu ka?)* — May I sit here? | *食べていいよ。 (Tabete ii yo.)* — You can eat (it's fine).\n\n**5. Prohibition (〜てはいけない):**\n*ここで写真を撮ってはいけません。 (Koko de shashin o totte wa ikemasen.)* — You must not take photos here.\n\n---\n\n# i-Adjectives vs na-Adjectives <!-- slug: adjectives -->\n\nJapanese adjectives come in two grammatically distinct types. Learning which is which determines whether you conjugate them.\n\n## i-Adjectives (い形容詞 i-keiyōshi)\n\nDictionary form ends in **い** (i). These **conjugate directly** — the い changes:\n\n| Form | Ending | Example (大きい ōkii — big) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Non-past positive | い | 大きい (big) |\n| Non-past negative | くない | 大きくない (not big) |\n| Past positive | かった | 大きかった (was big) |\n| Past negative | くなかった | 大きくなかった (was not big) |\n| Adverb | く | 大きく (largely/bigly) |\n\n*昨日の映画は面白かった。 (Kinō no eiga wa omoshirokatta.)* — Yesterday's movie was interesting.\n*このバッグは高くない。 (Kono baggu wa takakunai.)* — This bag is not expensive.\n\n⚠️ Exception: **いい (ii — good)** is irregular — its conjugated forms use **よ**: *よくない (yokunai — not good), よかった (yokatta — was good)*. よかった！ (Yokatta!) = \"That's great!\" / \"What a relief!\" — you'll hear this constantly.\n\n## na-Adjectives (な形容詞 na-keiyōshi)\n\nBefore a noun, they need **な (na)**. They do NOT directly inflect — they work more like nouns, conjugated through です:\n\n*静かな部屋 (shizuka na heya — quiet room) | 有名な人 (yūmei na hito — famous person)*\n\nConjugation uses です: *静かです / 静かじゃない / 静かでした / 静かじゃなかった*\n\nCommon na-adjectives: *好き (suki — liked/likeable), 嫌い (kirai — disliked), 上手 (jōzu — skillful), 下手 (heta — unskillful), 暇 (hima — free/bored), 大変 (taihen — tough), 有名 (yūmei — famous), 元気 (genki — healthy/energetic), 親切 (shinsetsu — kind)*\n\n✗ Trap: *好き* is a na-adjective, not a verb: *猫が好きです (neko ga suki desu)* = I like cats. NOT *猫を好きです* — use が, not を.\n\n---\n\n# The Copula です/だ <!-- slug: copula -->\n\n**です (desu)** is the polite copula. **だ (da)** is the plain/casual form.\n\n| Form | Polite | Plain |\n|---|---|---|\n| Non-past positive | です | だ |\n| Non-past negative | じゃないです / ではありません | じゃない / ではない |\n| Past positive | でした | だった |\n| Past negative | じゃなかったです / ではありませんでした | じゃなかった |\n\n*これはペンです。 (Kore wa pen desu.)* — This is a pen.\n*彼女は学生じゃない。 (Kanojo wa gakusei ja nai.)* — She is not a student. (plain)\n*昨日は暇でした。 (Kinō wa hima deshita.)* — Yesterday I was free.\n\nOne trap: です after i-adjectives is **optional decoration**, not the conjugating element: *大きいです* (polite) vs *大きい* (plain) — the い already carries the tense. ✗ ~~大きかったです~~ is technically allowed in modern usage but purists prefer ~~大きかった~~ in plain speech.\n\n---\n\n# Sentence-Final Particles ね and よ <!-- slug: ne-yo -->\n\nThese tiny particles communicate the speaker's stance and are absolutely central to sounding natural.\n\n## よ (yo) — new information, assertion\n\nThe speaker **informs** the listener of something they don't know. It asserts the speaker's knowledge:\n*あのレストランはおいしいですよ。 (Ano resutoran wa oishii desu yo.)* — That restaurant is good, you know. (I'm telling you — trust me.)\n*明日は雨ですよ。 (Ashita wa ame desu yo.)* — It's going to rain tomorrow. (heads up, you may not know)\n\n## ね (ne) — seeking agreement, shared feeling\n\nThe speaker **checks in** with the listener, seeks confirmation, or shares an experience:\n*いい天気ですね。 (Ii tenki desu ne.)* — Nice weather, isn't it? (I feel this, do you agree?)\n*このケーキはおいしいですね。 (Kono kēki wa oishii desu ne.)* — This cake is delicious, isn't it?\n\nCombined: **よね** = asserting AND seeking confirmation: *明日、会議がありますよね？ (Ashita, kaigi ga arimasu yo ne?)* — There's a meeting tomorrow, right? (I believe so — confirm?)\n\nOverusing よ sounds pushy (you're always correcting people). Overusing ね sounds indecisive. Native speakers calibrate these naturally — start with ね in social contexts.\n\n---\n\n# Politeness Levels & Keigo <!-- slug: keigo -->\n\nJapanese has a grammatically encoded **politeness system**. This is not just vocabulary choice — different verb forms exist for different social registers.\n\n## The main levels\n\n**Plain/casual (普通体 futsūtai / タメ口 tameguchi):**\nUsed with close friends, family, people younger/equal in status. Verbs in dictionary/た form, だ copula, no ます:\n*どこ行くの？ (Doko iku no?)* — Where are you going?\n\n**Polite (丁寧語 teineigo):**\nThe default safe register for most situations — strangers, workplaces, service contexts. Uses ます/です:\n*どちらへいらっしゃいますか。* — Where are you going? (formal)\n\n**Honorific language (敬語 keigo):**\nA full system of **humble speech** (謙譲語 kenjōgo — lowering yourself) and **respectful speech** (尊敬語 sonkeigo — elevating the other person). Used in business, with customers, with superiors.\n\nKey keigo verbs to recognize:\n\n| Plain | Humble (self) | Respectful (other) | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| いる | おる | いらっしゃる | to be/exist |\n| 行く | 参る (mairu) | いらっしゃる | to go |\n| 来る | 参る (mairu) | いらっしゃる | to come |\n| 食べる/飲む | いただく | めしあがる | eat/drink |\n| 言う | 申す (mōsu) | おっしゃる | to say |\n| する | いたす | なさる | to do |\n| もらう | いただく | くださる | to receive/give |\n\n*どうぞ召し上がってください。 (Dōzo meshiagatte kudasai.)* — Please go ahead and eat. (respectful — elevating the listener)\n*私がいたします。 (Watashi ga itashimasu.)* — I will do it. (humble — lowering self)\n\nFor beginners: learn polite ます/です first. Recognize keigo when you hear it. Producing keigo accurately takes years — even native Japanese learn it formally for job interviews.\n\n---\n\n# Comparisons <!-- slug: comparisons -->\n\n## より (yori) — than\n\n*AはBより〜です。 (A wa B yori ~ desu.)* — A is more ~ than B.\n\n*東京は大阪より大きいです。 (Tōkyō wa Ōsaka yori ōkii desu.)* — Tokyo is bigger than Osaka.\n*電車はバスより速い。 (Densha wa basu yori hayai.)* — Trains are faster than buses.\n\n## 〜のほうが (no hō ga) — … is more / the one that is more\n\n*AよりBのほうが〜です。 (A yori B no hō ga ~ desu.)* — B is more ~ than A. (comparing, selecting B as the higher)\n\n*バスより電車のほうが速い。 (Basu yori densha no hō ga hayai.)* — Trains are faster than buses. (lit: trains' side is faster)\n\nUsed in preference questions: *コーヒーと紅茶、どちらのほうが好きですか？ (Kōhī to kōcha, dochira no hō ga suki desu ka?)* — Which do you prefer, coffee or tea?\n\n## いちばん (ichiban) — most / number one\n\n*〜の中で、Aがいちばん〜です。 (〜no naka de, A ga ichiban ~ desu.)* — Among ~, A is the most ~.\n\n*クラスの中で、田中さんがいちばん背が高い。 (Kurasu no naka de, Tanaka-san ga ichiban se ga takai.)* — In the class, Tanaka is the tallest.\n\n---\n\n# The Four Conditionals <!-- slug: conditionals -->\n\nJapanese has four conditional forms where English has roughly two. Each carries a different nuance of conditionality.\n\n## と (to) — natural consequence / universal truth <!-- slug: to-conditional -->\n\n\"When X naturally happens, Y follows.\" Not for requests or willed outcomes.\n\n*右に曲がると、コンビニがあります。 (Migi ni magaru to, konbini ga arimasu.)* — If you turn right, there's a convenience store.\n*春になると、桜が咲く。 (Haru ni naru to, sakura ga saku.)* — When spring comes, the cherry blossoms bloom.\n*ボタンを押すと、ドアが開きます。 (Botan o osu to, doa ga akimasu.)* — When you press the button, the door opens.\n\n✗ Cannot use と for requests or intentions: ✗ ~~雨が降ると、家にいてください~~ — use たら or ば for that.\n\n## ば (ba) — hypothetical / emphatic condition <!-- slug: ba-conditional -->\n\nFocuses on the condition as a prerequisite. Often carries a nuance of \"as long as / provided that.\" Formed by changing the final う-row vowel to えば:\n*書く → 書けば (kakeba), 飲む → 飲めば (nomeba), 食べる → 食べれば (tabereba), する → すれば, 来る → 来れば*\n\n*もっと勉強すれば、合格できる。 (Motto benkyō sureba, gōkaku dekiru.)* — If you study more, you'll pass.\n*お金があれば、旅行に行くのに。 (Okane ga areba, ryokō ni iku noni.)* — If I had money, I'd go traveling. (counterfactual, with のに expressing regret)\n\nOften used in set phrases: *よければ (yokereba — if it's okay with you), なければ (nakereba — if there isn't)*\n\n## たら (tara) — upon completion / after / when (specific) <!-- slug: tara-conditional -->\n\nFormed by た-form + ら. Most versatile conditional — use this when unsure.\n\n*家に帰ったら、電話して。 (Ie ni kaettara, denwa shite.)* — When you get home, call me. (action completed → then do Y)\n*雨が降ったら、行きません。 (Ame ga futtara, ikimasen.)* — If it rains, I won't go.\n*宝くじが当たったら、世界旅行したい。 (Takarakuji ga atattara, sekai ryokō shitai.)* — If I won the lottery, I'd want to travel the world.\n\nたら can express past discovery: *窓を開けたら、猫がいた。 (Mado o aketara, neko ga ita.)* — When I opened the window, there was a cat.\n\n## なら (nara) — given that / if it's the case that <!-- slug: nara-conditional -->\n\nResponds to something just said or assumed. \"If what you're saying is true / if that's the situation.\"\n\n*日本に行くなら、京都に行ってみて。 (Nihon ni iku nara, Kyōto ni itte mite.)* — If you're going to Japan [as you say], try going to Kyoto.\n*それが本当なら、大変だ。 (Sore ga hontō nara, taihen da.)* — If that's true, it's serious.\n*安いなら、買う。 (Yasui nara, kau.)* — If it's cheap [as you say], I'll buy it.\n\nなら responds to context — it doesn't assert the condition; it **accepts** information just given and draws a conclusion.\n\n**Summary comparison:**\n\n| Conditional | Core feel | Example situation |\n|---|---|---|\n| と | automatic, natural law | turn the key → engine starts |\n| ば | prerequisite/hypothetical | provided you study → you'll pass |\n| たら | upon completing / specific if | when you arrive → call me |\n| なら | given what you told me | if you're going to Tokyo → visit Shinjuku |\n\n---\n\n# Describing a Movie <!-- slug: describing-a-movie -->\n\n**Convention**: narrate plot in **non-past** (present) form — same as English.\n\n**Opening:**\n*この映画は〜についての話です。 (Kono eiga wa ~ ni tsuite no hanashi desu.)* — This movie is a story about ~.\n*映画の舞台は〜です。 (Eiga no butai wa ~ desu.)* — The setting of the movie is ~.\n*主人公は〜という人物です。 (Shujinkō wa ~ to iu jinbutsu desu.)* — The protagonist is a character called ~.\n\n**Genre vocabulary:**\n*コメディ (komedi — comedy), サスペンス (saspensu — thriller/suspense), ドラマ (dorama — drama), アクション (akushon — action), ホラー (horā — horror), SF (esu-efu — sci-fi), アニメ (anime — animation), ドキュメンタリー (dokyumentarī — documentary)*\n\n**Plot narration (non-past):**\n*主人公は〜しようとしますが、〜という問題が起きます。 (Shujinkō wa ~ shiyō to shimasu ga, ~ to iu mondai ga okimasu.)* — The protagonist tries to ~, but a problem arises where ~.\n\n**Opinion:**\n- *面白かったです。 (Omoshirokatta desu.)* — It was interesting. (past i-adjective)\n- *感動しました。 (Kandō shimashita.)* — I was moved.\n- *ストーリーが予想外でした。 (Sutōrī ga yosōgai deshita.)* — The story was unexpected.\n- *おすすめです。 (Osusume desu.)* — I recommend it.\n- *ちょっと長すぎました。 (Chotto nagasugimashita.)* — It was a bit too long. (*すぎる sugiru* = too much — attach to adjective stem or verb stem)\n\n**Key vocabulary:**\n*監督 (kantoku — director), 俳優 (haiyū — actor), 女優 (joyū — actress), 主人公 (shujinkō — protagonist), 悪役 (akuyaku — villain), セリフ (serifu — dialogue/lines), 字幕 (jimaku — subtitles), 吹き替え (fukikae — dubbing), 結末 (ketsumatsu — ending), 演技 (engi — acting performance)*\n";
